         <abstract>
            <p>In many practical problems in numerical differention of a function $f(x)$ that is known, observed, measured, or found experimentally to limited accuracy, the computing error is often much more significant than the truncating error In numerical differentiation of the $n$-point Lagrangian interpolation polynomial, i.e., $f^{(k)}(x) \sim \Sigma^n_{i=1} L^{n(k)}_i (x)f(x_i)$, a criterion for optimal stability is minimization of $\Sigma^n_{i=1} |L^{n(k)}_i(x)|$. Let $L \equiv L(n, k, x_1,\ldots, x_n; x \text{or} x_0) = \Sigma^n_{i=1}| L^{n(k)}_i(x \text{or} x_0)|$. For $x_i$ and fixed $x = x_0$ in $\lbrack -1, 1 \rbrack$, one problem is to find the $n x_i$'s to give $L_0 \equiv L_0(n, k, x_0) = \min L$. When the truncation error is negligible for any $x_0$ within $\lbrack -1, 1 \rbrack$, a second problem is to find $x_0 = x^\ast$ to obtain $L^\ast \equiv L^\ast (n, k) = \min L_0 = \min \min L$. A third much simpler problem, for $x_i$ equally spaced, $x_1 = -1, x_n = 1$, is to find $\overline x$ to give $\overline L \equiv \overline L(n, k) - \min L$. For lower values of $n$, some results were obtained on $L_0$ and $L^\ast$ when $k = 1$, and on $\overline L$ when $k = 1$ and 2 by direct calculation from available tables of $L^{n(k)}_i(x)$. The relation of $L_0, L^\ast$ and $\overline L$ to equally spaced points, Chebyshev points, Chebyshev polynomials $T_m(x)$ for $m \leqslant n - 1$, minimax solutions, and central difference formulas, considering also larger value of $n$, is indicated sketchily.</p>
